      "name": "Hirundo",
      "rank": "GENUS",
      "description": "Barn swallows — the most familiar swallows on Earth and one of the most widespread birds in the world. The barn swallow (ladusvala) is a summer visitor of immense cultural significance in Sweden: its arrival in late April or early May is celebrated as a defining moment of the Nordic year. Swallows have lived alongside humans for millennia, nesting in barns, stables, and buildings and feeding on the insects attracted to livestock — a mutualistic relationship that has made them simultaneously dependent on and beloved by farming communities. Swallows are aerial masters, capable of sustained flight speeds exceeding 70 km/h and catching all their food on the wing. They are long-distance migrants, wintering in sub-Saharan Africa and covering up to 10,000 km each way.",
