      "id": "GENUS_DELICHON",
      "name": "Delichon",
      "rank": "GENUS",
      "description": "House martins — compact, blue-black and white swallows that build dome-shaped mud nests attached to cliff faces and — most famously — under the eaves of houses. The common house martin (hussvala) is a familiar summer visitor to Swedish towns and villages, and established colonies under roof eaves can be decades old. House martins collect mud for nest construction from puddles and stream banks, sometimes travelling considerable distances from their nesting site. They are more colonial than barn swallows, often building nests immediately adjacent to one another. Despite their name and intimate association with human buildings, relatively little is known about their winter quarters in sub-Saharan Africa.",
      "lineage": "Martins",
      "children": [
        {
          "id": "DELICHON_URBICUM",
          "name": "Delichon urbicum",
          "rank": "SPECIES",
          "commonName": "Western house martin",
          "lineage": "Martins",
          "continents": [
            "Europe",
            "Asia",
            "Africa"
          ],
          "subspeciesCount": 3,
          "description": "The western house martin, sometimes called the common house martin, northern house martin or, particularly in Europe, just house martin, is a migratory passerine bird of the swallow family which breeds in Europe, north Africa and west-central Asia; and winters in sub-Saharan Africa and southwestern Asia. It feeds on insects which are caught in flight, and it migrates to climates where flying insects are plentiful. It has a blue head and upperparts, white rump and pure white underparts, and is found in both open country and near human habitation.",
          "sourcedFrom": "wikipedia"
        },
