      "name": "Ptyonoprogne",
      "rank": "GENUS",
      "description": "Crag martins — robust, earth-coloured swallows of rocky mountains and gorges. The Eurasian crag martin nests on cliff faces and rocky outcrops, plastering a mud cup to vertical rock surfaces in locations completely inaccessible to terrestrial predators. They are resident year-round in southern Europe's mountain ranges, one of the few swallows that don't make long-distance migrations. In Sweden, crag martins are rare vagrants rather than breeding birds, occasionally seen along coastal cliffs in autumn. Their flight is more leisurely and gliding than other swallows, matching the thermal-soaring conditions of mountain environments.",
